article.headline: (14) WISCONSIN 64, PENNSYLVANIA 53
article.story: PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Wisconsin coach Bo Ryan knows the Palestra well. The Badgers learned about the arena Friday night. Devin Harris scored 16 points, including a three-point play late in the game, as No. 15 Wisconsin beat Penn 64-53 on Friday night in a scrappy, defensive matchup. Ryan, from nearby Chester, Pa., played and watched several games in the Palestra when he was growing up and said he was nervous about opening the season against a good team in a place with so much tradition. He did a pretty good job of keeping his thoughts to himself. "I tried not to tell them too much," Ryan said. "I didn't want to make it about me coming back here. I think they just got a little anxious. When you watch Penn and the way they work, you better be sound fundamentally or you won't walk out with your head high." The Badgers were able to leave with a win, Ryan said, because Harris -- just 4-for-14 from the field -- continued to work hard and had just one turnover. Zach Morley and Freddie Owens added 12 points apiece for the Badgers, who opened the season without injured forward Alando Tucker. Jeff Schiffner led Penn with 20 points, including three 3-pointers. Schiffner tied the game 40-all with 11:28 to play with a 3-pointer, and the Quakers stayed within four points until 2:55 remained. That's when Harris hit a runner in the lane and was fouled. He hit the free throw and Wisconsin led by five. Owens followed with a pair of layups and a free-throw to put the game away for the Badgers. "I thought our guys did a good job of anticipating without getting beat back door," Ryan said. "I've never seen that many deflections in that short a period of time." Wisconsin was just 17-of-28 from the free-throw line, and Owens, an 82 percent free-throw shooter last season, was 2-of-8 against Penn. Morley, a junior-college transfer, had 10 first-half points after coming off the bench three minutes into the game. He also had four offensive rebounds while playing an upbeat, physical game in the paint. "That's what I try to do. Bang people inside," Morley said. I'm happy with the way I played. I'm just glad to get my first game out of way." Early in the first half, Harris hit a 3-pointer on an attempted alley-oop pass to Morley that gave Wisconsin its first lead of the game, 17-15. It came in the midst of an 12-0 run that put the Badgers up by nine. It was the only 3-pointer in 14 attempts for Wisconsin. "We're not going to put that one on our highlight tape of how to shoot the three," Ryan said. "But when you go 1-for-14, show me any team that's ever won." Tim Begley hit a first-half, buzzer-beater from just inside the half-court line to cut the Wisconsin lead to eight. Jan Fikiel added 10 points for Penn. No other Quakers reached double-figures. "There are a lot of positives that will come out of this game," Penn coach Fran Dunphy said. "I'm sure we'll look at the tape and say, 'If we didn't make this mistake, maybe it would be a two-point advantage instead of a deficit."
